            <p>The <addressee>Revd Isaac Leeser</addressee></p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">My Dear Sir,</p>
            <p rend="indent(2)">Unavoidable engage<lb/>ments prevented my complacence with<lb/> the
                orders of the board of Managers to<lb/> furnish you with a copy of the reports<lb/>
                read at their anniversary meeting<lb/> in time for its insertion in the
                Occident<lb/> for the present month, but if you can<lb/> find space in your next No.
                they will<lb/> feel honored by its being placed on its<lb/> pages. Have the goodness
                    <add>?</add> to say<lb/> that the 30th anniversary meeting was held on the
                    <date>7th<lb/> Nov. 1849</date> officers chosen &amp; the Reports<lb/> read but
                do not publish names. I have<lb/> always disliked the ostentation of seeing<lb/>
                Ladies names in print, when the whole<lb/> amount of their services are so very<lb/>
                small â€” and the mere <add>?</add> they go<lb/> about doing good the better</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Believe me very sincerely my</p>
            <p>Dear sir, your friend &amp;c</p>
            <p rend="indent(2)">
                <persName role="author">R Gratz</persName>
            </p>
        </body>
